title.narrative: 502 EARLY CHILDHOOD EDUCATION

description.narrative: National and state governments have increased capacity to ensure age and developmentally appropriate pre-primary education for school readiness, which contributes to Access To Quality Learning Opportunities, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Innovation, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

title.narrative: National and state governments have increased capacity to ensure age and developmentally appropriate pre-primary education forschool readiness

description.narrative: Approximately 9 million (49% girls) preschoolers benefited from responsive parenting as frontline workers (FLW) and community volunteers promoted playful parenting, disseminating activity calendars, audio-video stories, songs, worksheets in 11 states. UNICEF supported Ministry of Education (MoE) develop national guidelines promoting parental participation for ;home-based learning for 54 million 3-8-year-old (49% girls). More than 11 million children (49% girls) benefited from UNICEF technical support at national and state level for developing plans, budgets, programme guidance, curriculum and capacity building resources for strengthening early childhood education in 0.3 million ECD centres located in schools as recommended in National Education Policy (NEP). | Status:On-track | As-of Date:09/01/2022
